<p><b>Sino-Soviet split</b> was a gradual worsening of relations between the <a href="/wiki/People%27s_Republic_of_China" title="People's Republic of China">People's Republic of China</a> (PRC) and the <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Union of Soviet Socialist Republics</a> (USSR) during the <a href="/wiki/Cold_War" title="Cold War">Cold War</a>. There is no particular date or event which marked the onset of the split, for tensions had plagued the Sino-Soviet alliance even at its best, but there was growing divergence between the two countries from about 1956. The confrontation reached its peak in the late 1960s and continued in various ways until the late 1980s. It led to a parallel split in the international <a href="/wiki/Communism" title="Communism">Communist</a> movement, although the split had as much to do with Chinese and Soviet <a href="/wiki/National_interest" title="National interest">national interests</a> as with the two countries' respective communist ideologies.</p>
